Cessation of use, practice, or exercise; inusitation; desuetude; as, the limbs lose their strength by disuse

disutilize.definition: To deprive of utility; to render useless

diswarn.definition: To dissuade from by previous warning

diswitted.definition: Deprived of wits or understanding; distracted

diswont.definition: To deprive of wonted usage; to disaccustom

disworship.definition: To refuse to worship; to treat as unworthy
A deprivation of honor; a cause of disgrace; a discredit

disworth.definition: To deprive of worth; to degrade

disyoke.definition: To unyoke; to free from a yoke; to disjoin

ditation.definition: The act of making rich; enrichment

ditch.definition: A trench made in the earth by digging, particularly a trench for draining wet land, for guarding or fencing inclosures, or for preventing an approach to a town or fortress. In the latter sense, it is called also a moat or a fosse
Any long, narrow receptacle for water on the surface of the earth
To dig a ditch or ditches in; to drain by a ditch or ditches; as, to ditch moist land
To throw into a ditch; as, the engine was ditched and turned on its side
To dig a ditch or ditches

dite.definition: To prepare for action or use; to make ready; to dight

dithecal.definition: Having two thecæ, cells, or compartments

ditheist.definition: One who holds the doctrine of ditheism; a dualist

ditto.definition: The aforesaid thing; the same (as before). Often contracted to do., or to two “turned commas” (”), or small marks.  Used in bills, books of account, tables of names, etc., to save repetition

ditty.definition: A saying or utterance; especially, one that is short and frequently repeated; a theme
A song; a lay; a little poem intended to be sung
To sing; to warble a little tune

ditty-box.definition: A small box to hold a sailor's thread, needless, comb, etc

diuretic.definition: Tending to increase the secretion and discharge of urine

diureticalness.definition: The quality of being diuretical; diuretic property

diurna.definition: A division of Lepidoptera, including the butterflies; -- so called because they fly only in the daytime

diurnal.definition: Relating to the daytime; belonging to the period of daylight, distinguished from the night; -- opposed to nocturnal; as, diurnal heat; diurnal hours

Daily; recurring every day; performed in a day; going through its changes in a day; constituting the measure of a day; as, a diurnal fever; a diurnal task; diurnal aberration, or diurnal parallax; the diurnal revolution of the earth
Opening during the day, and closing at night; -- said of flowers or leaves
Active by day; -- applied especially to the eagles and hawks among raptorial birds, and to butterflies (Diurna) among insects

diurnation.definition: The condition of sleeping or becoming dormant by day, as is the case of the bats

divagation.definition: A wandering about or going astray; digression

divalent.definition: Having two units of combining power; bivalent.  Cf. Valence

divan.definition: A book; esp., a collection of poems written by one author; as, the divan of Hafiz

A cushioned seat, or a large, low sofa or couch; especially, one fixed to its place, and not movable

divaricate.definition: To part into two branches; to become bifid; to fork
To divide into two branches; to cause to branch apart
Forking and diverging; widely diverging; as the branches of a tree, or as lines of sculpture, or color markings on animals, etc

divarication.definition: A separation into two parts or branches; a forking; a divergence
An ambiguity of meaning; a disagreement of difference in opinion
A divergence of lines of color sculpture, or of fibers at different angles

dive.definition: To plunge into water head foremost; to thrust the body under, or deeply into, water or other fluid

To plunge (a person or thing) into water; to dip; to duck

A plunge headforemost into water, the act of one who dives, literally or figuratively

divedapper.definition: A water fowl; the didapper. See Dabchick

diver.definition: One who, or that which, dives
Fig.: One who goes deeply into a subject, study, or business
Any bird of certain genera, as Urinator (formerly Colymbus), or the allied genus Colymbus, or Podiceps, remarkable for their agility in diving

diverge.definition: To extend from a common point in different directions; to tend from one point and recede from each other; to tend to spread apart; to turn aside or deviate (as from a given direction); -- opposed to converge; as, rays of light diverge as they proceed from the sun

divers.definition: Different in kind or species; diverse

diversely.definition: In different directions; to different points

diversifiability.definition: The quality or capacity of being diversifiable

diversifiable.definition: Capable of being diversified or varied

diversification.definition: The act of making various, or of changing form or quality

diversified.definition: Distinguished by various forms, or by a variety of aspects or objects; variegated; as, diversified scenery or landscape

diversifier.definition: One who, or that which, diversifies

diversiform.definition: Of a different form; of varied forms

diversify.definition: To make diverse or various in form or quality; to give variety to; to variegate; to distinguish by numerous differences or aspects

diversion.definition: The act of turning aside from any course, occupation, or object; as, the diversion of a stream from its channel; diversion of the mind from business
That which diverts; that which turns or draws the mind from care or study, and thus relaxes and amuses; sport; play; pastime; as, the diversions of youth

diversionary.definition: likely or designed to confuse or deceive; -- of tactics

diversity.definition: A state of difference; dissimilitude; unlikeness

diversory.definition: Serving or tending to divert; also, distinguishing

divert.definition: To turn aside; to turn off from any course or intended application; to deflect; as, to divert a river from its channel; to divert commerce from its usual course

diverter.definition: One who, or that which, diverts, turns off, or pleases

diverticle.definition: A turning; a byway; a bypath

diverticulum.definition: A blind tube branching out of a longer one

divertissement.definition: A short ballet, or other entertainment, between the acts of a play

divertive.definition: Tending to divert; diverting; amusing; interesting

dives.definition: The name popularly given to the rich man in our Lord's parable of the “Rich Man and Lazarus” (Luke xvi. 19-31). Hence, a name for a rich worldling

divest.definition: To unclothe; to strip, as of clothes, arms, or equipage; -- opposed to invest

To make partition of among a number; to apportion, as profits of stock among proprietors; to give in shares; to distribute; to mete out; to share
To disunite in opinion or interest; to make discordant or hostile; to set at variance

To mark divisions on; to graduate; as, to divide a sextant

To be separated; to part; to open; to go asunder

To have a share; to partake

divided.definition: Cut into distinct parts, by incisions which reach the midrib; -- said of a leaf

dividend.definition: A sum of money to be divided and distributed; the share of a sum divided that falls to each individual; a distribute sum, share, or percentage; -- applied to the profits as appropriated among shareholders, and to assets as apportioned among creditors; as, the dividend of a bank, a railway corporation, or a bankrupt estate
A number or quantity which is to be divided

divider.definition: One who, or that which, divides; that which separates anything into parts
One who deals out to each his share
One who, or that which, causes division
An instrument for dividing lines, describing circles, etc., compasses. See Compasses
a vertical structure that divides or separates (as a wall divides one room from another)

dividing.definition: That divides; separating; marking divisions; graduating

dividual.definition: Divided, shared, or participated in, in common with others

divination.definition: The act of divining; a foreseeing or foretelling of future events; the pretended art discovering secret or future by preternatural means
An indication of what is future or secret; augury omen; conjectural presage; prediction

divinator.definition: One who practices or pretends to divination; a diviner

divine.definition: Of or belonging to God; as, divine perfections; the divine will
Proceeding from God; as, divine judgments
Appropriated to God, or celebrating his praise; religious; pious; holy; as, divine service; divine songs; divine worship
Pertaining to, or proceeding from, a deity; partaking of the nature of a god or the gods
Godlike; heavenly; excellent in the highest degree; supremely admirable; apparently above what is human. In this application, the word admits of comparison; as, the divinest mind
One skilled in divinity; a theologian
A minister of the gospel; a priest; a clergyman
To foresee or foreknow; to detect; to anticipate; to conjecture
To foretell; to predict; to presage
To use or practice divination; to foretell by divination; to utter prognostications
To have or feel a presage or foreboding
To conjecture or guess; as, to divine rightly

divinely.definition: In a divine or godlike manner; holily; admirably or excellently in a supreme degree
By the agency or influence of God

divineness.definition: The quality of being divine; superhuman or supreme excellence

A conjecture; a guesser; one who makes out occult things

diving.definition: That dives or is used or diving

divinity.definition: The state of being divine; the nature or essence of God; deity; godhead
The Deity; the Supreme Being; God
A pretended deity of pagans; a false god
A celestial being, inferior to the supreme God, but superior to man
Something divine or superhuman; supernatural power or virtue; something which inspires awe
The science of divine things; the science which treats of God, his laws and moral government, and the way of salvation; theology

divisibility.definition: The quality of being divisible; the property of bodies by which their parts are capable of separation

divisible.definition: Capable of being divided or separated

division.definition: The act or process of diving anything into parts, or the state of being so divided; separation
That which divides or keeps apart; a partition
The portion separated by the divining of a mass or body; a distinct segment or section
Disunion; difference in opinion or feeling; discord; variance; alienation
Difference of condition; state of distinction; distinction; contrast

To separate or disunite; to sunder
To make away; to put away
