duffel bag.definition: A sack to hold miscellaneous articles, as tools, supplies, or the like

duffer.definition: A peddler or hawker, especially of cheap, flashy articles, as sham jewelry; hence, a sham or cheat

dufrenite.definition: A mineral of a blackish green color, commonly massive or in nodules. It is a hydrous phosphate of iron

dug.definition: A teat, pap, or nipple; -- formerly that of a human mother, now that of a cow or other beast

dugong.definition: An aquatic herbivorous mammal (Halicore dugong), of the order Sirenia, allied to the manatee, but with a bilobed tail. It inhabits the Red Sea, Indian Ocean, East Indies, and Australia

dugout.definition: A canoe or boat dug out from a large log
A house made partly in a hillside or slighter elevation

a structure on the edge of the playing field in foul territory, partly below ground and partly above ground, open toward the playing field but roofed and with the other three sides closed.  It is typically long and narrow, having benches where the players may sit when not on the playing field; as, the foul ball was tipped into the dugout

dugway.definition: A way or road dug through a hill, or sunk below the surface of the land

duke.definition: A leader; a chief; a prince
In England, one of the highest order of nobility after princes and princesses of the royal blood and the four archbishops of England and Ireland
In some European countries, a sovereign prince, without the title of king
The fists; as, put up your dukes

dukedom.definition: The title or dignity of a duke

dukeship.definition: The quality or condition of being a duke; also, the personality of a duke

dukhobors.definition: A Russian religious sect founded about the middle of the 18th century at Kharkov. They believe that Christ was wholly human, but that his soul reappears from time to time in mortals. They accept the Ten Commandments and the “useful” portions of the Bible, but deny the need of rulers, priests, or churches, and have no confessions, icons, or marriage ceremonies. They are communistic, opposed to any violence, and unwilling to use the labor of animals. Driven out of Russia proper, many have emigrated to Cyprus and Canada. See Raskolnik, below

dulcamara.definition: A plant (Solanum Dulcamara). See Bittersweet, n., 3 (a)

dulcamarin.definition: A glucoside extracted from the bittersweet (Solanum Dulcamara), as a yellow amorphous substance. It probably occasions the compound taste. See Bittersweet, 3(a)

dulcet.definition: Sweet to the ear; melodious; harmonious

dulciana.definition: A sweet-toned stop of an organ

dulcification.definition: The act of dulcifying or sweetening

dulcify.definition: To sweeten; to free from acidity, saltness, or acrimony
Fig. : To mollify; to sweeten; to please

dulcimer.definition: An instrument, having stretched metallic wires which are beaten with two light hammers held in the hands of the performer

dulcite.definition: A white, sugarlike substance, C6H8.(OH)2, occurring naturally in a manna from Madagascar, and in certain plants, and produced artificially by the reduction of galactose and lactose or milk sugar

dulcorate.definition: To sweeten; to make less acrimonious

duledge.definition: One of the dowels joining the ends of the fellies which form the circle of the wheel of a gun carriage

dulia.definition: An inferior kind of veneration or worship, given to the angels and saints as the servants of God

dull.definition: Slow of understanding; wanting readiness of apprehension; stupid; doltish; blockish
Slow in action; sluggish; unready; awkward
Not keen in edge or point; lacking sharpness; blunt
Not bright or clear to the eye; wanting in liveliness of color or luster; not vivid; obscure; dim; as, a dull fire or lamp; a dull red or yellow; a dull mirror
Heavy; gross; cloggy; insensible; spiritless; lifeless; inert

Furnishing little delight, spirit, or variety; uninteresting; tedious; cheerless; gloomy; melancholy; depressing; as, a dull story or sermon; a dull occupation or period; hence, cloudy; overcast; as, a dull day
To deprive of sharpness of edge or point
To make dull, stupid, or sluggish; to stupefy, as the senses, the feelings, the perceptions, and the like
To render dim or obscure; to sully; to tarnish
To deprive of liveliness or activity; to render heavy; to make inert; to depress; to weary; to sadden

dull-eyed.definition: Having eyes wanting brightness, liveliness, or vivacity

duller.definition: One who, or that which, dulls

dullness.definition: The state of being dull; slowness; stupidity; heaviness; drowsiness; bluntness; obtuseness; dimness; want of luster; want of vividness, or of brightness

dully.definition: In a dull manner; stupidly; slowly; sluggishly; without life or spirit

dulse.definition: A seaweed of a reddish brown color, which is sometimes eaten, as in Scotland. The true dulse is Sarcophyllis edulis; the common is Rhodymenia. [Written also dillisk.]

duly.definition: In a due, fit, or becoming manner; as it (anything) ought to be; properly; regularly

dumal.definition: Pertaining to, or set with, briers or bushes; brambly

dumb.definition: Destitute of the power of speech; unable; to utter articulate sounds; as, the dumb brutes
Not willing to speak; mute; silent; not speaking; not accompanied by words; as, dumb show
Lacking brightness or clearness, as a color
Lacking intelligence; having poor judgment; stupid; dull-witted; -- of persons
Exhibiting poor judgment or lack of wisdom; leading predictably to unfavorable consequences; -- of actions

dumb down.definition: To render simpler, so as to be comprehensible or usable by unintelligent people; to simplify; -- of texts or devices

dumb-waiter.definition: A framework on which dishes, food, etc., are passed from one room or story of a house to another; a lift for dishes, etc.; also, a piece of furniture with movable or revolving shelves

dumbbell.definition: An exercising weight, consisting of two spheres or spheroids, connected by a short bar for a handle; used (often in pairs) for gymnastic exercise

synonyms: Syn. -- dummy, dope, boob, booby, pinhead.

Syn. -- confuse, perplex, throw, fox, befuddle, fuddle, bedevil, puzzle, mystify, baffle, bewilder, flummox, stupefy, stupify, nonplus, gravel, amaze, trounce, confound, be confusing to, make confused.
Syn. -- amazed, astonied, astonished, astounded, flabbergasted, stunned, stupefied, thunderstruck.

dumbness.definition: The quality or state of being dumb; muteness; silence; inability to speak

dumdum bullet.definition: A kind of man-stopping bullet, designed to fragment inside the body and thus inflict a severed and painful wound; -- so named from Dumdum, in India, where bullets are manufactured for the Indian army

dumfound.definition: To strike dumb; to confuse with astonishment

synonyms: Syn. -- amazed, astonied, astonished, astounded, flabbergasted, stunned, stupefied, thunderstruck.

dummy.definition: Silent; mute; noiseless; as a dummy engine
Fictitious or sham; feigned; as, a dummy watch
A sham package in a shop, or one which does not contain what its exterior indicates

An imitation or copy of something, to be used as a substitute; a model; a lay figure; as, a figure on which clothing is exhibited in shop windows; a blank paper copy used to show the size of the future book, etc
One who plays a merely nominal part in any action; a sham character
An ignorant or thick-witted person; a foolish person; a dolt
synonyms: Syn. -- dope, boob, booby, pinhead, dumbbell.

dummy.definition: A locomotive with condensing engines, and, hence, without the noise of escaping steam; also, a dummy car
The fourth or exposed hand when three persons play at a four-handed game of cards
A floating barge connected with a pier

dump.definition: A thick, ill-shapen piece; a clumsy leaden counter used by boys in playing chuck farthing
A dull, gloomy state of the mind; sadness; melancholy; low spirits or a mild depression; despondency; ill humor; -- now used only in the plural
A melancholy strain or tune in music; any tune
To put or throw down with more or less of violence; hence, to unload from a cart by tilting it; as, to dump sand, coal, etc
A car or boat for dumping refuse, etc
A ground or place for dumping ashes, refuse, etc
A pile of ore or rock

synonyms: Syn. -- dumping car, dumping cart, dump car.

dump truck.definition: a truck, usually with an open top, the carrying bopdy of which can be tilted so as to emptied its contents without handling

dumpage.definition: The act of dumping loads from carts, especially loads of refuse matter; also, a heap of dumped matter
A fee paid for the privilege of dumping loads; called in some cases tipping fee

dumpcart.definition: a cart that can be tilted to empty the contents without handling them

dumped.definition: p. p. of dump, v. t.; as, The money was there, dumped all over the floor

dumple.definition: To make dumpy; to fold, or bend, as one part over another

dumpling.definition: A roundish mass of dough boiled in soup, or as a sort of pudding; often, a cover of paste inclosing an apple or other fruit, and boiled or baked; as, an apple dumpling

dumps.definition: a gloomy mental state; same as 2nd dump{1}; -- used mostly in the phrase “in the dumps”

dumpy.definition: Short and thick; of low stature and disproportionately stout

dumpy level.definition: A level having a short telescope (hence its name) rigidly fixed to a table capable only of rotatory movement in a horizontal plane. The telescope is usually an inverting one. It is sometimes called the Troughton level, from the name of the inventor, and a variety improved by one Gavatt is known as the Gavatt level

dumuzi.definition: the Sumerian and Babylonian god of pastures and vegetation; consort of Inanna

dun.definition: To cure, as codfish, in a particular manner, by laying them, after salting, in a pile in a dark place, covered with salt grass or some like substance
To ask or beset (e.g., a debtor), for payment; to urge importunately
An urgent request or demand of payment; as, he sent his debtor a dun
Of a dark color; of a color partaking of a brown and black; of a dull brown color; swarthy

dunbird.definition: The pochard; -- called also dunair, and dunker, or dun-curre

dunce.definition: One backward in book learning; a child or other person dull or weak in intellect; a dullard; a dolt

duncedom.definition: The realm or domain of dunces

dunder.definition: The lees or dregs of cane juice, used in the distillation of rum

dunderhead.definition: A dunce; a numskull; a blockhead

dune.definition: A low hill of drifting sand usually formed on the coats, but often carried far inland by the prevailing winds

dunfish.definition: Codfish cured in a particular manner, so as to be of a superior quality

dung.definition: To immerse or steep, as calico, in a bath of hot water containing cow dung; -- done to remove the superfluous mordant

dungaree.definition: A coarse kind of unbleached cotton fabric; blue denim
Trousers, overalls or similar work clothes made of blue denim

dungeon.definition: A close, dark prison, commonly, under ground, as if the lower apartments of the donjon or keep of a castle, these being used as prisons
To shut up in a dungeon

dunghill.definition: Any mean situation or condition; a vile abode

dungmeer.definition: A pit where dung and weeds rot for manure

dungy.definition: Full of dung; filthy; vile; low

dungyard.definition: A yard where dung is collected

dunker.definition: One of a religious denomination whose tenets and practices are mainly those of the Baptists, but partly those of the Quakers; -- called also Tunkers, Dunkards, Dippers, and, by themselves, Brethren, and German Baptists, and they call their denomination the Church of the Brethren

dunkerque.definition: the name of a town and a battle fought there, in World War II (1940) when 330,000 Allied troops had to be evacuated from the beaches at Dunkirk in a desperate retreat under enemy fire.  Most of the forces were safely evacuated to England

dunkirk.definition: the name of a town and a battle fought there, in World War II (1940) when 330,000 Allied troops had to be evacuated from the beaches at Dunkirk in a desperate retreat under enemy fire.  Most of the forces were safely evacuated to England

dunlin.definition: A species of sandpiper (Tringa alpina); -- called also churr, dorbie, grass bird, and red-backed sandpiper. It is found both in Europe and America

dunnage.definition: Fagots, boughs, or loose materials of any kind, laid on the bottom of the hold for the cargo to rest upon to prevent injury by water, or stowed among casks and other cargo to prevent their motion

dunner.definition: One employed in soliciting the payment of debts

dunno.definition: A slang shortening of I don't know or don't know; as, dunno where I lost my keys; Where'd he go?  I dunno

dunnock.definition: The hedge sparrow or hedge accentor

duo.definition: A composition for two performers; a duet

duodecimal.definition: Proceeding in computation by twelves; expressed in the scale of twelves
A twelfth part; as, the duodecimals of an inch
A system of numbers, whose denominations rise in a scale of twelves, as of feet and inches. The system is used chiefly by artificers in computing the superficial and solid contents of their work

duodecimo.definition: Having twelve leaves to a sheet; as, a duodecimo from, book, leaf, size, etc
A book consisting of sheets each of which is folded into twelve leaves; hence, indicating, more or less definitely, a size of a book; -- usually written 12mo or 12°

duodenal.definition: Of or pertaining to the duodenum; as, duodenal digestion

duodenary.definition: Containing twelve; twelvefold; increasing by twelves; duodecimal

duodenum.definition: The part of the small intestines between the stomach and the jejunum. See Illust. of Digestive apparatus, under Digestive

duograph.definition: A picture printed from two half-tone plates made with the screen set at different angles, and usually printed in two shades of the same color or in black and one tint

duoliteral.definition: Consisting of two letters only; biliteral

duotone.definition: Any picture printed in two shades of the same color, as duotypes and duographs are usually printed

duotype.definition: A print made from two half-tone plates made from the same negative, but etched differently

dup.definition: To open; as, to dup the door

dupe.definition: One who has been deceived or who is easily deceived; a gull; as, the dupe of a schemer
To deceive; to trick; to mislead by imposing on one's credulity; to gull; as, dupe one by flattery

dupery.definition: The act or practice of duping

dupion.definition: A double cocoon, made by two silkworms

duplex.definition: organized so that data may be transmitted in two opposite directions over the same channel; -- of communications channels, such as data transfer lines between computers
To arrange, as a telegraph line, so that two  messages may be transmitted simultaneously; to equip with a duplex telegraphic outfit
something which is duplex; -- used mostly in reference to a living unit, such as an apartment, in a building having two similar living units
a double-stranded region in a nucleic acid molecule.  See deoxyribonucleic acid

duplexer.definition: a device which switches electronic circuitry so that a radio antenna can function as either a transmitting or receiving antenna

duplicate.definition: That which exactly resembles or corresponds to something else; another, correspondent to the first; hence, a copy; a transcript; a counterpart
An original instrument repeated; a document which is the same as another in all essential particulars, and differing from a mere copy in having all the validity of an original
To double; to fold; to render double
To make a duplicate of (something); to make a copy or transcript of
To divide into two by natural growth or spontaneous action; as, infusoria duplicate themselves

duplication.definition: The act of duplicating, or the state of being duplicated; a doubling; a folding over; a fold
The act or process of dividing by natural growth or spontaneous action; as, the duplication of cartilage cells

duplicative.definition: Having the quality of duplicating or doubling
Having the quality of subdividing into two by natural growth

duplicature.definition: A doubling; a fold, as of a membrane

duplicity.definition: Doubleness of heart or speech; insincerity; a sustained form of deception which consists in entertaining or pretending to entertain one set of feelings, and acting as if influenced by another; bad faith
The use of two or more distinct allegations or answers, where one is sufficient

dur.definition: Major; in the major mode; as, C dur, that is, C major

dura mater.definition: The tough, fibrous membrane, which lines the cavity of the skull and spinal column, and surrounds the brain and spinal cord; -- frequently abbreviated to dura

durability.definition: The state or quality of being durable; the power of uninterrupted or long continuance in any condition; the power of resisting agents or influences which tend to cause changes, decay, or dissolution; lastingness

durable.definition: Able to endure or continue in a particular condition; lasting; not perishable or changeable; not wearing out or decaying soon; enduring; as, durable cloth; durable happiness

durableness.definition: Power of lasting, enduring, or resisting; durability

durably.definition: In a lasting manner; with long continuance

dural.definition: Pertaining to the dura, or dura mater

duralumin.definition: an aluminum-based alloy which is both light and strong, containing 4 per cent of copper and 0.5 per cent of magnesium and smaller amounts of iron, manganese, and silicon.  It hardens with aging at room temperature

duramen.definition: The heartwood of an exogenous tree

durance.definition: Imprisonment; restraint of the person; custody by a jailer; duress. Shak
A stout cloth stuff, formerly made in imitation of buff leather and used for garments; a sort of tammy or everlasting
In modern manufacture, a worsted of one color used for window blinds and similar purposes

durante.definition: During; as, durante vita, during life; durante bene placito, during pleasure

duration.definition: The state or quality of lasting; continuance in time; the portion of time during which anything exists

durbar.definition: An audience hall; the court of a native prince; a state levee; a formal reception of native princes, given by the governor general of India

dure.definition: To last; to continue; to endure

durene.definition: A colorless, crystalline, aromatic hydrocarbon, C6H2(CH3)4, off artificial production, with an odor like camphor

duress.definition: Hardship; constraint; pressure; imprisonment; restraint of liberty

The state of compulsion or necessity in which a person is influenced, whether by the unlawful restrain of his liberty or by actual or threatened physical violence, to incur a civil liability or to commit an offense

duressor.definition: One who subjects another to duress

durham.definition: One or a breed of short-horned cattle, originating in the county of Durham, England. The Durham cattle are noted for their beef-producing quality

durian.definition: The fruit of the durio.  It is oval or globular, and eight or ten inches long.  It has a hard prickly rind, containing a soft, cream-colored pulp, of a most delicious flavor and a very offensive odor.  The seeds are roasted and eaten like chestnuts

during.definition: In the time of; as long as the action or existence of; as, during life; during the space of a year

durio.definition: A fruit tree (Durio zibethinus, the only species known) of the Indian Archipelago.  It bears the durian

durometer.definition: An instrument for measuring the degree of hardness; especially, an instrument for testing the relative hardness of steel rails and the like

durra.definition: A kind of millet, cultivated throughout Asia, and introduced into the south of Europe; a variety of Sorghum vulgare; -- called also Indian millet, and Guinea corn

durst.definition: of Dare. See Dare, v. i

durukuli.definition: A small, nocturnal, South American monkey of the genus Aotus (formerly Nyctipthecus trivirgatus). The owl monkey.  See douroucouli

durylic.definition: Pertaining to, allied to, or derived from, durene; as, durylic acid

duse.definition: A demon or spirit. See Deuce

dushanbe.definition: The capital city of Tajikistan.  Population (2000) = 524,000

dusk.definition: Tending to darkness or blackness; moderately dark or black; dusky
Imperfect obscurity; a middle degree between light and darkness; twilight; as, the dusk of the evening

dusky.definition: Partially dark or obscure; not luminous; dusk; as, a dusky valley
Tending to blackness in color; partially black; dark-colored; not bright; as, a dusky brown

dust.definition: Fine, dry particles of earth or other matter, so comminuted that they may be raised and wafted by the wind; that which is crumbled to minute portions; fine powder; as, clouds of dust; bone dust
A single particle of earth or other matter
The earth, as the resting place of the dead
The earthy remains of bodies once alive; the remains of the human body
Figuratively, a low or mean condition
To free from dust; to brush, wipe, or sweep away dust from; as, to dust a table or a floor
To reduce to a fine powder; to levigate

dust storm.definition: A strong windstorm that lifts particles of dust or dry soil into the air and blows them around, covering land or objects with a thick layer of dust.  Dust storms may occur in arable areas during periods of drought; when a similar storm occurs in a desert area, such a storm is called a sandstorm

dustbin.definition: a bin that holds rubbish until it is collected
synonyms: Syn. -- ashcan, trash can, garbage can, wastebin, ashbin, trash barrel, trash bin.

dustbrush.definition: A brush of feathers, bristles, or hair, for removing dust from furniture

dustcart.definition: a truck for collecting domestic refuse; as, in England a garbage truck is called a dustcart

dustcloth.definition: A piece of cloth used for wiping dust from objects or surfaces

duster.definition: One who, or that which, dusts; a utensil that frees from dust
A device for spreading a powder, especially one for spreading insecticide on plants
A pitch intentionally thrown by a pitcher directly at or very close to the batter, intended to make the batter stand further away from home plate; also called a dust-back pitch or a dust-back

dustless.definition: Without dust; as a dustless path

dustman.definition: One whose employment is to remove dirt and refuse; a garbage man

dustmop.definition: a dry mop for dusting floors

dustpan.definition: A shovel-like utensil with a short handle used for conveying away dust brushed from the floor

synonyms: Syn. -- quarrel, wrangle, row, words, run-in.

dusty.definition: Filled, covered, or sprinkled with dust; clouded with dust; as, a dusty table;  a dusty attic; also, reducing to dust
Like dust; of the color of dust; as, a dusty white

dutch.definition: Pertaining to Holland, or to its inhabitants

dutchman.definition: A native, or one of the people, of Holland

dutchman's breeches.definition: a delicate perennial spring-flowering herb (Dicentra cucullaria) of eastern U.S., having  peculiar double-spurred white flowers.  See Illust. of Dicentra

dutchman's-pipe.definition: a hardy deciduous American vine (Aristolochia durior) having large, heart-shaped leaves and bearing brownish-purple flowers which have their calyx tubes curved like the bowl of a tobacco pipe.  Formerly classified as Aristolochia Sipho
synonyms: Syn. -- pipe vine, Aristolochia macrophylla, Aristolochia durior.

duteous.definition: Fulfilling duty; dutiful; having the sentiments due to a superior, or to one to whom respect or service is owed; obedient; as, a duteous son or daughter

dutiable.definition: Subject to the payment of a duty; as dutiable goods

dutiful.definition: Performing, or ready to perform, the duties required by one who has the right to claim submission, obedience, or deference; submissive to natural or legal superiors; obedient, as to parents or superiors; as, a dutiful son or daughter; a dutiful ward or servant; a dutiful subject
Controlled by, proceeding from, a sense of duty; respectful; deferential; as, dutiful affection

duty.definition: That which a person is bound by moral obligation to do, or refrain from doing; that which one ought to do; service morally obligatory
Hence, any assigned service or business; as, the duties of a policeman, or a soldier; to be on duty
Specifically, obedience or submission due to parents and superiors
Respect; reverence; regard; act of respect; homage

The efficiency of an engine, especially a steam pumping engine, as measured by work done by a certain quantity of fuel; usually, the number of pounds of water lifted one foot by one bushel of coal (94 lbs. old standard), or by 1 cwt. (112 lbs., England, or 100 lbs., United States)
Tax, toll, impost, or customs; excise; any sum of money required by government to be paid on the importation, exportation, or consumption of goods

duumvir.definition: One of two Roman officers or magistrates united in the same public functions

duumviral.definition: Of or belonging to the duumviri or the duumvirate

duumvirate.definition: The union of two men in the same office; or the office, dignity, or government of two men thus associated, as in ancient Rome

dux.definition: The scholastic name for the theme or subject of a fugue, the answer being called the comes, or companion

duykerbok.definition: A small South African antelope (Cephalous mergens); -- called also impoon, and deloo

dvergr.definition: A dwarf supposed to dwell in rocks and hills and to be skillful in working metals

dwale.definition: The deadly nightshade (Atropa Belladonna), having stupefying qualities
The tincture sable or black when blazoned according to the fantastic system in which plants are substituted for the tinctures

dwang.definition: A piece of wood set between two studs, posts, etc., to stiffen and support them

dwarf.definition: An animal or plant which is much below the ordinary size of its species or kind

A diminutive human being, small in stature due to a pathological condition which causes a distortion of the proportions of body parts to each other, such as the limbs, torso, and head.  A person of unusually small height who has normal body proportions is usually called a midget
A small, usually misshapen person, typically a man, who may have magical powers; mythical dwarves were often depicted as living underground in caves
To hinder from growing to the natural size; to make or keep small; to stunt
To become small; to diminish in size

dwarfish.definition: Like a dwarf; below the common stature or size; very small; petty; as, a dwarfish animal, shrub

dwell.definition: To abide; to remain; to continue
To abide as a permanent resident, or for a time; to live in a place; to reside

dweller.definition: An inhabitant; a resident; as, a cave dweller

dwelling.definition: Habitation; place or house in which a person lives; abode; domicile

dwindle.definition: To diminish; to become less; to shrink; to waste or consume away; to become degenerate; to fall away
To make less; to bring low
The process of dwindling; dwindlement; decline; degeneracy

dwindlement.definition: The act or process of dwindling; a dwindling

dwindling.definition: the act or process of becoming gradually less until little remains; as, there is no greater sadness that the dwindling away of a family

dwine.definition: To waste away; to pine; to languish

dy.definition: the chemical symbol for dysprosium, a rare earth element of atomic number 66

dyad.definition: Two units treated as one; a couple; a pair
An element, atom, or radical having a valence or combining power of two
Having a valence or combining power of two; capable of being substituted for, combined with, or replaced by, two atoms of hydrogen; as, oxygen and calcium are dyad elements. See Valence

dyadic.definition: Pertaining to the number two; of two parts or elements

dyaks.definition: The aboriginal and most numerous inhabitants of Borneo. They are partially civilized, but retain many barbarous practices

dyas.definition: A name applied in Germany to the Permian formation, there consisting of two principal groups

dyaus.definition: the Hindu god of the sky

dyaus-pitar.definition: the Hindu god of the sky; same as Dyaus

dybbuk.definition: the wandering soul of a dead person, or a demon, that enters the body of a living person and controls that body's behavior.  It may be exorcised by religious rites

dye.definition: To stain; to color; to give a new and permanent color to, as by the application of dyestuffs
Material used for dyeing; a dyestuff

dyed.definition: having a new color imparted by impregnation with dye; having an artificially produced color; not naturally colored

dyed-in-the-wool.definition: thoroughly imbued; thoroughgoing; uncompromising; complete; unmitigated; through-and-through
dyed before being spun or woven into cloth

dyehouse.definition: A building in which dyeing is carried on

dyeing.definition: The process or art of fixing coloring matters permanently and uniformly in the fibers of wool, cotton, etc

dyer.definition: One whose occupation is to dye cloth and the like

dyer's broom.definition: small Eurasian shrub (Genista tinctoria) having clusters of yellow flowers that yield a dye; common as weed in England and U.S.; sometimes grown as an ornamental
synonyms: Syn. -- woodwaxen, dyer's greenweed, dyer's weed, dyer's rocket, dyeweed, greenweed, whin, woadwaxen, Genista tinctoria.

dyewood.definition: Any wood from which coloring matter is extracted for dyeing

dying.definition: In the act of dying; destined to death; mortal; perishable; as, dying bodies
Of or pertaining to dying or death; as, dying bed; dying day; dying words; also, simulating a dying state
The act of expiring; passage from life to death; loss of life

dyingly.definition: In a dying manner; as if at the point of death

dyingness.definition: The state of dying or the stimulation of such a state; extreme languor; languishment

dynactinometer.definition: An instrument for measuring the intensity of the photogenic (light-producing) rays, and computing the power of object glasses

dynam.definition: A unit of measure for dynamical effect or work; a foot pound. See Foot pound

dynameter.definition: An instrument for determining the magnifying power of telescopes, consisting usually of a doubleimage micrometer applied to the eye end of a telescope for measuring accurately the diameter of the image of the object glass there formed; which measurement, compared with the actual diameter of the glass, gives the magnifying power

dynamic.definition: Of or pertaining to dynamics; belonging to energy or power; characterized by energy or production of force
Relating to physical forces, effects, or laws; as, dynamical geology

dynamic ram.definition: a type of random access memory using circuits that require periodic refresh cycles in order to retain the stored information.  Contrasted to static ram, which maintains the memory state as long as the power is still applied

dynamically.definition: In accordance with the principles of dynamics or moving forces

dynamics.definition: That branch of mechanics which treats of the motion of bodies (Kinematics) and the action of forces in producing or changing their motion (kinetics). Dynamics is held by some recent writers to include statics and not kinematics
The moving moral, as well as physical, forces of any kind, or the laws which relate to them
That department of musical science which relates to, or treats of, the power of tones

dynamism.definition: The doctrine of Leibnitz, that all substance involves force

dynamist.definition: One who accounts for material phenomena by a theory of dynamics

dynamitard.definition: A political dynamiter. [A form found in some newspapers.]

dynamite.definition: An explosive substance consisting of nitroglycerin absorbed by some inert, porous solid, as infusorial earth, sawdust, etc. It is safer than nitroglycerin, being less liable to explosion from moderate shocks, or from spontaneous decomposition

dynamiter.definition: One who uses dynamite; esp., one who uses it for the destruction of life and property

dynamiting.definition: Destroying by dynamite, for political ends

dynamization.definition: The act of setting free the dynamic powers of a medicine, as by shaking the bottle containing it

dynamo-electric.definition: Pertaining to the development of electricity, especially electrical currents, by power; producing electricity or electrical currents by mechanical power

dynamograph.definition: A dynamometer to which is attached a device for automatically registering muscular power

dynamometer.definition: An apparatus for measuring force or power; especially, muscular effort of men or animals, or the power developed by a motor, or that required to operate machinery

dynamometric.definition: Relating to a dynamometer, or to the measurement of force doing work; as, dynamometrical instruments

dynamometry.definition: The art or process of measuring forces doing work

dynast.definition: A ruler; a governor; a prince

dynastic.definition: Of or relating to a dynasty or line of kings

dynastidan.definition: One of a group of gigantic, horned beetles, including Dynastus Neptunus, and the Hercules beetle (Dynastus Hercules) of tropical America, which grow to be six inches in length

dynasty.definition: A race or succession of kings, of the same line or family; the continued lordship of a race of rulers

dyne.definition: The unit of force, in the C. G. S. (Centimeter Gram Second) system of physical units; that is, the force which, acting on a gram for a second, generates a velocity of a centimeter per second

dys-.definition: An inseparable prefix, fr. the Greek dys- hard, ill, and signifying ill, bad, hard, difficult, and the like; cf. the prefixes, Skr. dus-, Goth. tuz-, OHG. zur-, G. zer-, AS. to-, Icel. tor-, Ir. do-

dysaesthesia.definition: Impairment of any of the senses, esp. of touch

dyscrasia.definition: An ill habit or state of the constitution; -- formerly regarded as dependent on a morbid condition of the blood and humors

dyscrasite.definition: A mineral consisting of antimony and silver

dysenteric.definition: Of or pertaining to dysentery; having dysentery; as, a dysenteric patient

dysentery.definition: A disease attended with inflammation and ulceration of the colon and rectum, and characterized by griping pains, constant desire to evacuate the bowels, and the discharge of mucus and blood

dysfunctional.definition: impaired in function; especially of a bodily system or organ
failing to serve an adjustive purpose; -- of a trait or condition; as, dysfunctional behavior

dysgenesic.definition: Not procreating or breeding freely; as, one race may be dysgenesic with respect to another

dysgenesis.definition: A condition of not generating or breeding freely; infertility; a form of homogenesis in which the hybrids are sterile among themselves, but are fertile with members of either parent race

dysgenics.definition: the study of the operation of factors causing degeneration in the type of offspring produced

dyskinesia.definition: an abnormality in performing voluntary muscle movements

dyslectic.definition: Suffering from dyslexia; having impaired ability to comprehend written words; a condition usually associated with a neurologic disorder

dyslexia.definition: Any of various reading disorders caused by a damaged or congenitally faulty structure within the central nervous system, and causing an impairment of the ability to interpret spatial relationships or to integrate auditory and visual information.  A common example is when letter sequences are interpreted as inverted in order, as in bat/tab

dyslogistic.definition: Unfavorable; not commendatory; -- opposed to eulogistic

dysluite.definition: A variety of the zinc spinel or gahnite

dyslysin.definition: A resinous substance formed in the decomposition of cholic acid of bile; -- so called because it is difficult to solve

dysnomy.definition: Bad legislation; the enactment of bad laws

dysodile.definition: An impure earthy or coaly bitumen, which emits a highly fetid odor when burning

dyspepsia.definition: A kind of indigestion; a state of the stomach in which its functions are disturbed, without the presence of other diseases, or, if others are present, they are of minor importance. Its symptoms are loss of appetite, nausea, heartburn, acrid or fetid eructations, a sense of weight or fullness in the stomach, etc

dyspeptic.definition: Pertaining to dyspepsia; having dyspepsia; as, a dyspeptic or dyspeptical symptom

dyspeptone.definition: An insoluble albuminous body formed from casein and other proteid substances by the action of gastric juice

dysphagia.definition: Difficulty in swallowing, or inability to swallow

dysphonia.definition: A difficulty in producing vocal sounds; enfeebled or depraved voice

dysphoria.definition: Impatience under affliction; morbid restlessness; dissatisfaction; the fidgets

dyspnoic.definition: Affected with shortness of breath; relating to dyspnœa

dysprosium.definition: An element of the rare earth-group. Symbol Dy; at. wt., 162.5

dysteleology.definition: The doctrine of purposelessness; a term applied by Haeckel to that branch of physiology which treats of rudimentary organs, in view of their being useless to the life of the organism

dysuria.definition: Difficult or painful discharge of urine

dysuric.definition: Pertaining to, or afflicted with, dysury

dzeren.definition: The Chinese yellow antelope (Procapra gutturosa), a remarkably swift-footed animal, inhabiting the deserts of Central Asia, Tibet, and China

dziggetai.definition: The kiang, a wild horse or wild ass of Tibet (Asinus hemionus)

débouchure.definition: The outward opening of a river, of a valley, or of a strait
